COURSE DESCRIPTION
The purpose of this course is to help you grasp important microeconomic principles and how they can be utilized to better understand market behavior and dynamics, underlying incentives, and public programs and policies in the healthcare sector. 
The course is divided into three sections. The first section examines core microeconomic theories and concepts, discussing them in general terms and providing specific examples of how they apply to the US health sector. The second section uses this economic framework to examine the behavior of physicians, hospitals, and pharmaceutical manufacturers in the health care market. The final section of this course will extend this framework to examine the structure, market behavior and public policies related to the private insurance industry, as well as the structure and financial/economic aspects of the Medicare and Medicaid programs. Throughout all sections, the role of the consumer and the incentives of the various stakeholders will be examined. 
PREREQUISITES 
None 
COURSE COMPETENCIES AND LEARNING OBJECTIVES
The Department of Health Policy and Management has adopted a carefully researched Competency Model to guide the design of all courses in the Management curriculum. Each course is explicitly charged with reinforcing and developing further a number of key competencies identified in the model. This course also is intended to assess and further your professional development and career readiness. The course focuses specifically on the following competencies:
●	Analytic Thinking: Breaking down problems to understand and assess basic relationships and to recognize and analyze complex relationships
●	Innovative Thinking: Using fundamental concepts to recognize patterns and develop unique responses to complex ideas
●	Performance Measurement: Using evidence-based approaches
●	Health Policy: Understanding the history and structure of the US health care system; issues of quality, access, and cost, insurance systems and provider payment methods and specifying how a variety of forces, particularly political and economic ones, have shaped the system; analyzing the main options and methods for financing health services.
These competencies are reflected and implemented throughout all activities in the course and inform the specific course learning objectives described below. Students who successfully complete this course will be better able to:
●	Understand the factors that influence the demand and supply of health care services
●	Apply the concepts of allocative efficiency, production efficiency and opportunity costs in considering the implications of increasing health care spending on societal welfare
●	Analyze and anticipate the behavior of providers, consumers, insurers and other health sector actors in response to changes in economic/financial incentives
●	Utilize tools such as cost-benefit and cost-effectiveness analysis to support health care-related decision-making
●	Assess past, present and emerging trends in health care delivery, payment systems, and public policy and understand the impacts, implications and inter-connectedness of these developments
●	Understand the dynamics within the private health insurance marketplace as well as the features and roles played by the Medicare and Medicaid programs.
●	Consider the appropriate role of government policies, regulations and programs in promoting an efficient and equitable health care system.
ASSESSMENT AND GRADING POLICY
Student grades will be based on the following components :
●	Take home problem sets: there will be 5 problem sets throughout the semester, valued at 5% each. The lowest assignment score will be dropped; we will average only the top 4 assignment scores when computing your final grade for the course. 
●	In class exams: there will be 3 exams for this course, worth 25% each. The exams will be closed book and administered using proctor on your laptop. One 8.5 x 11 sheet of notes may be used. Please bring your laptops for exam days. 
●	Attendance: Attendance and participation are required, valued at 5% of your total grade. Attendance will be taken throughout the course. Attendance policies for this course with respect to infections disease will follow the Mailman school’s policies on this topic. A copy of those policies can be found in the files section of the course’s Canvas site. 
Late Policy: Assignments will be due on Wednesday of the following week at noon. 5% of your assignment grade will be deducted for every hour that your assignment is late (this means that if the assignment is submitted between 12:01-1:00pm, 5% of your grade will be deducted and so on). No assignments will be accepted following the start of class. 
Grading 
A+               	Reserved for highly exceptional achievement.
A                 	Excellent. Outstanding achievement.
A-                	Excellent work, close to outstanding.
B+               	Very good. Solid achievement expected of most graduate students.
B                 	Good. Acceptable achievement.
B-                	Acceptable achievement, but below what is generally expected of graduate students.
C+               	Fair achievement, above minimally acceptable level.
C                 	Fair achievement, but only minimally acceptable.
C-                	Very low performance.
F                  	Failure. Course usually may not be repeated unless it is a required course.
 
Letter grades will be adjusted as necessary to comply with the HPM department’s guidelines, which are:

GRADE	% OF CLASS
A- To A+	~40-55%
B- to B+	~40-55%
C+ & Below	Remainder
 
However, in no case will this adjustment reduce your letter grade below what it would be following a traditional translation from a numeric to a letter grade [i.e., a final numeric grade of 90 or above would translate to an A- A, or A+, depending on where it would fall in the 90 to 100 range; a final numeric grade in the 80 to 89 range would convert to a B-, B, or B+, depending on where it fell in that range; a final numeric grade below 80 would convert to a C+ or below.)
Notes on Grading
If you identify an error in the grading of your work, please bring this to the TA’s attention as soon as possible so we can fix it. Aside from attempts to remedy grading errors, requests to re-grade a question on an assignment or exam may result in the re-grading of that entire assignment or exam, which may result in a lower overall score. All requests for re-grades must be made within seven days from the date that the graded assignments/exams are returned to the class. 
We are always available to help explain assignment and exam questions. If you have questions about your grade, please feel free to reach out to the TA for clarification. 
