COURSE MATERIALS
There will be no required textbook for the class. Readings will primarily take the form of articles drawn from academic journals in the fields of health policy, economics, and medicine, as well as the popular press, and textbook excerpts. Exam questions will be based on subjects discussed in lectures. 
You are free to choose any micro or health economics textbook to support this class if you like; here is one recommendation: 
Krugman, Paul and Wells, Robin. Microeconomics, 3rd Edition. Worth Publishers, 2013. [ISBN-13 Number: 978-1-4292-8342-7]. This is a “fun” easy-to-read text written by a Nobel Prize-winning economist – how often can you say that? Don’t buy the more expensive newer versions – the 3rd edition will be just fine (my page references in this syllabus will be to this edition). Used paperback copies are available on Amazon: https://smile.amazon.com/gp/offer-listing/1429283424/ref=sr_1_3?sprefix=krugman+micr%2Caps%2C136&crid=2DBAP0XCXJW8H&keywords=krugman+microeconomics&qid=1589829807&sr=8-3&dchild=1
There are also many excellent Health Economics textbooks available at the Health Sciences Library, which you may check out if you so choose. 
For those of you who have not taken a course in microeconomics before, many students have found the microeconomics module on the Kahn Academy website to be a helpful and straightforward reference for reviewing key concepts.
If you’re looking for a ‘backup’ or secondary source for any economics concepts with which you might be having some trouble, the (free) online textbook by CORE Econ is a good comprehensive reference.
You will see that several of the readings for this module are prepared by the Kaiser Family Foundation (KFF). KFF frequently puts timely, concise, well-research issue briefs describing important features of the Medicaid or important program trends or hot-button issues. If you ever find yourself working in this space (or in a provider organization or health system serving significant numbers of Medicaid recipients, their website (https:/ /www.kff.org) is a great place to go for solid info and analysis on the program.
