Academic Integrity
Students are required to adhere to the Mailman School Conduct and Community Standards, which includes the Code of Academic Integrity. Columbia Mailman and Columbia University take academic integrity very seriously. This instructor and course are no different. Should any student be suspected of an academic integrity violation, there will be a report submitted to the Center for Student Success & intervention/Student Conduct. After these offices conduct their process, if a student is found responsible for violating an academic integrity policy (see Standards & Discipline/Academic Violations and Student Honor Code & Professional Guidelines), they will be assigned a grade penalty, with a possible outcome being a 0% on the assignment.
Please review the university, school, and course policies, as you are responsible for behaving according to the outlined expectations.
Personal Support
Students sometimes experience life challenges that require additional support and connection to resources. If you are experiencing difficult circumstances, please reach out for help and support. Student Support Services in the Office of Student Affairs is poised to connect with students, provide resource referrals, and provide ongoing, non-clinical support. They are a good place to start if you do not know where to turn.
If you would like to make a referral to student support, whether for yourself or someone else, the best way to do so is to fill out the form linked below, and student support will reach out directly. You may also email Meurcie Zignoli at mz3047@cumc.columbia.edu to connect to Student Support Services. Please note that this form is separate from other reporting structures in place for code of conduct violations or Title VI/ Title IX concerns. This form is also not an emergency response mechanism. In case of an emergency, please contact Public Safety at 212-305-7972: Mailman Student Support Team Referral Form (maxient.com).
Disability Services and Accommodations
I am committed to a learning environment that is inclusive of all students, including students with disabilities. You are always welcome to reach out to me or to the Office of Disability Services (ODS) to discuss academic accommodations.
In order to receive disability-related academic accommodations, students must first be registered with the Office of Disability Services (ODS). Students who have or think they may have a disability are invited to contact ODS for a confidential discussion at 212.854.2388 (V) 212.854.2378 (TTY), or by email at disability@columbia.edu. If you have already registered with ODS, please speak to your instructor to ensure that they have been notified of your recommended accommodations by Meredith Ryer (mr4075@cumc.columbia.edu), Assistant Director of Student Support and Mailman’s liaison to the Office of Disability Services.
If you have registered with ODS, I encourage you to contact me to ensure that they have notified me of their recommended accommodations.
Bias Incidents
Our community at Columbia University’s Mailman School of Public Health is committed to creating an inclusive working, learning, and living environment where all are respected. The occurrence of bias related incidents, involving conduct, speech, or expressions reflecting prejudice are an opportunity for learning and growing as a community.
As part of our efforts to create as inclusive a community as possible, when bias incidents occur at Columbia, we provide an opportunity for those involved to engage in education, advocacy and conversation. In this way, we work to address the incident and minimize the potential for future occurrences. Our community’s tools to address bias include a reporting process and the Bias Incident Resource Team, plus resources within schools and various offices. You can access information about the Bias Reporting Process and FAQs here.
Why Reporting Matters and How to File a Report
Our priority is ensuring that Columbia University is a safe community and workplace where we can learn, live, work and express ourselves. As members of the community, we have a shared responsibility to uphold these standards and report behavior that violates these standards. The reporting options provide Columbia University community members an opportunity to share important information directly with appropriate offices. If you or a member of the community needs support please take the time to complete a report so we may provide support, care, and accountability: https://universitylife.columbia.edu/report

 
COURSE SCHEDULE
Details on each session are posted in the Modules page. Please complete the readings uploaded to the Module pages corresponding to each class. 

Week 1: Introduction to the Economics of Health Care
1/21/26	Learning Objectives:
●	Provide an overview of the course, introduction to teaching team
●	Discuss core economic concepts
●	Explore the extent to which the health care sector differs from other industries, how these differences affect the functioning of an efficient market
●	Examine selected overall system performance metrics and the opportunity cost implications of high levels of health care spending.
 
Week 2: The Demand for / Consumption of Medical Care
1/28/26	Learning Objectives:
●	Understand utility & utility maximization
●	Examine the factors that influence consumers’ demand for medical care
●	Understand elasticities and why they are important
Reading: Please see Session Module in Canvas
 Problem Set #1 Assigned 

 

Week 3: The Supply / Production of Medical Care                                                        	
2/4/26	Learning Objectives:
●	Examine the factors that influence the supply of health care services available in the marketplace
●	Understand cost functions, and how they relate to the supply of medical care
●	Understand the concepts of marginal rate of technical substitution and cost-minimizing decision-making
●	Problem Set #1 Review 
Problem Set #1 Due 
Problem Set #2 Assigned 

 Week 4:  Market Analysis
2/11/26	Learning Objectives:
●	Describe and analyze models of market structure – perfect competition, oligopoly, and monopoly markets – and introduce/discuss their relevance to the markets for different types of health care services and their implications for price levels and other aspects of market performance.
●	Introduce market power and market concentration and how they relate and describe the approaches commonly used to define relevant markets and measure the extent of market concentration.
Problem Set #2 Due

 

Week 5: Exam I 
2/18/26	Exam I will cover all material until this point 
A review session will be scheduled prior to the exam

Week 6: Hospitals 
2/24/26	Learning Objectives:
●	 Approaches to paying for hospital services
●	 Examine the shifts that occurred in the supply and utilization of hospital services in response to payment changes
●	 Understand the factors precipitating the trend toward increased concentration within hospital markets and examine research findings on the impact of increased consolidation on prices and care quality
●	Examine the variability in hospital payment levels that exist within and across hospital markets.
Reading: Please see Session Module in Canvas
Problem Set #3 Assigned 

 
Week 7: Physicians                                           	
3/04/26	Learning Objectives:
●	Supply of physicians in the US, including the distribution across specialties, employment status and income levels
●	Evolution of approaches to paying for physician services
●	 Explore the dynamic shifts that occurred in the physician practice arrangements that have occurred over time, including increased horizontal and vertical consolidation
●	Examine the findings of health services research on the impact of these organizational changes on health care utilization, prices, and quality.
Problem Set 3 Due 
Problem Set 4 Assigned 

Week 8: The Pharmaceutical Industry
3/11/26	Learning Objectives:
●	Provide an overview of the pharmaceutical industry, discussing how it is similar to and differs from the markets for other medical services.
●	Examine the issues and relationships related to innovation/research & development, prices and profits in this sector.
●	Discuss the factors, including government policies, that affect the competitiveness of the pharmaceutical market.
●	Introduce the range of players involved in pharmaceutical supply chain, with a focus on pharmaceutical benefit managers (PBMs) and the controversial role they play within that structure.
Problem Set 4 Due



Week 9: Cost-Benefit and Cost-Effectiveness Analysis                  	
3/25/26	Learning Objectives:
Understand what is meant by cost-benefit and cost-effectiveness analysis, the difference in the questions that each type of analysis can address, and the technical and conceptual issues associated with conducting such analyses to assist in health care-related decision-making.

Week 10:  In-Class Exam on Part II Material
4/1/26	This exam will cover all material up until this point in the course. It will be heavily weighted on the second part of the course, but may contain some references to the first part. 
A review session will be scheduled prior to the exam. 

Week 10: Health Insurance Part I 
4/08/26	Learning Objectives:
●	Provide a context for examining the private insurance market
●	Describe the underlying economic theory/concepts and factors related to consumer demand for health insurance, including the tax-treatment of employer sponsored health insurance
●	Describe the different markets (individual, small group, large group); how they differ from one another in terms of dynamics, regulation, etc.
●	Examine the extent of consolidation in the health insurance market
●	Describe the trends in the types of health insurance plans being sold (e.g, HMOs, PPOs, etc.) and the differences in how these different plan types are designed.
  
Week 11: Health Insurance Part II 
4/15/26	Learning Objectives:
●	Explore private health insurance markets in the pre-ACA days
●	Summarize the major ACA provisions affecting the private health insurance market
●	Examine the performance of the ACA-authorized Health Insurance Marketplaces/Exchanges with respect to reducing the number of uninsured, premium levels, and insurer participation
●	Highlight current & potential future directions for the private insurance industry.
Problem set 5 assigned 
 
Week 12: Medicaid
4/22/26	Learning Objectives:
●	Better understand the following aspects of the Medicaid program:
○	Its origins and its current roles within the health care system and the economy
○	The basics: Population characteristics and eligibility, benefits, administration & financing, and expenditures
○	Medicaid’s link with the Medicare program: The “Dual Eligible” population
○	The ACA’s Medicaid expansion provisions and their impacts
○	Medicaid dynamics during the COVID-19 pandemic
○	Medicaid reform proposals that have been considered by Congress in the past (and that we may see again).

Problem set 5 Due 

Week 14: Medicare
4/29/26	Learning Objectives:
●	Better understand the following aspects of the Medicare program:
○	Its origins and its current roles within the health care system and the economy
○	The basics: Population characteristics and eligibility, and expenditures, the differences across the various program “parts”: Parts A through D, including benefits and funding; and the program’s overall financial stability
○	The differences between “traditional” Medicare and the Medicare Advantage program.
Note: The Kaiser Family Foundation is a great source of information on the Medicare program.
 
Week 15: Final Exam
5/7/26	The exam will be focused primarily on Part III material but may touch on all course content. 
Time: 5:30 to 8:20pm in HSC401


 
 

